{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #87: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. Let $\\epsilon >0$. Is it true that, if $k$ is sufficiently large, then\\[R(G)>(1-\\epsilon)^kR(k)\\]for every graph $G$ with chromatic number $\\chi(G)=k$?\n\nEven stronger, is there some $c>0$ such that, for all large $k$, $R(G)>cR(k)$ for every graph $G$ with chromatic number $\\chi(G)=k$? Current best: Since $R(k)\\leq 4^k$ this is trivial for $\\epsilon\\geq 3/4$. Yuval Wigderson points out that $R(G)\\gg 2^{k/2}$ for any $G$ with chromatic number $k$ (via a random colouring), which asymptotically matches the best-known lower bounds for $R(k)$. Prize: no. OEIS: A059442. Tags: graph theory, ramsey theory.","id":"vf_6881a87882fc9ac1","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 87 (PR #3588) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/3588.","id":"vf_6b2b70a9814f0eb6","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/87.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_6881a87882fc9ac1","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:87","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_6b2b70a9814f0eb6","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:87","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_6b2b70a9814f0eb6","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"vf_6881a87882